## Superseded from e2e-runner-hang-signal-fixes

```yaml
name: e2e-runner-hang-signal-fixes
description: "Fix E2E experiment runner hanging and ignoring Ctrl+C/Ctrl+Z signals during parallel execution."
category: debugging
date: 2026-03-18
version: 1.0.0
```

Six hang/signal bugs fixed: (1) as_completed() + future.result() → wait(timeout=2.0, FIRST_COMPLETED); (2) proc.communicate(timeout=3600) → polling helper with shutdown check; (3) stdin=subprocess.DEVNULL to prevent inherited stdin hangs; (4) shutdown check in rate limit sleep loop; (5) timeout on _resume_event.wait(); (6) SIGTSTP removed from generic signal installer. Key: communicate(timeout=N) does NOT consume partial output on TimeoutExpired — safe to call in a loop. Verified on ProjectScylla PR #1515; 4924 tests pass, 77.74% coverage.

---

## Superseded from python-subprocess-terminal-corruption

```yaml
name: python-subprocess-terminal-corruption
description: "Fix terminal corruption from Python subprocess management and None-safe error handling patterns."
category: debugging
date: 2026-02-13
version: 1.0.0
```

Three bugs: (1) subprocess.run without stdin=subprocess.DEVNULL allows child (e.g. Node.js CLI) to alter terminal settings then crash without restoring; (2) dict.get("key", "default") returns None when key exists with None value — use or coalescing; (3) code reading flat JSON keys when actual JSON is nested. Fix: stdin=subprocess.DEVNULL + _restore_terminal() in finally, or coalescing, match actual JSON structure.

---

## Superseded from cross-cpu-survey-gha-only-crash

```yaml
name: cross-cpu-survey-gha-only-crash
description: "Fan a GHA-extracted container image out across a tailnet of physical machines to narrow a 'GHA-only crash' bug class."
category: debugging
date: 2026-05-12
version: "1.0.0"
verification: verified-local
```

Multi-host CPU survey to falsify GHA-only crash hypotheses. Key: rsync tar to jumphost, fan out via ssh from jumphost (not from laptop), run 50 iterations per host for statistical confidence, capture /proc/cpuinfo atomically with the result. Critical finding: Hyper-V on AMD Zen 4 masks AVX-512 CPUID bits while LLVM may emit AVX-512 based on CPU-name fingerprinting — explaining why GHA Azure runners crash while all surveyed non-AVX-512 Intel CPUs run clean. Verified on ProjectOdyssey modular/modular#6413 bisect.

